File: Russian President Vladimir Putin greets South African President Cyril Ramaphosa during the official welcoming ceremony for the heads of state and government of states participating in the 2019 Russia-Africa Summit in Sochi on October 23, 2019. JOHANNESBURG - President Cyril Ramaphosa has had a phone call with Russian President, Vladimir Putin.   
The phone call dealt with the invasion of Ukraine and the ongoing war. Ramaphosa says South Africa has been asked to play a mediation role in ending the conflict. READ: Putin says sanctions will disrupt food, energy markets South Africa was approached to mediate due to its historical ties to Russia and as a member of BRICS. Ramaphosa says the conflict must be resolved through mediation and negotiation, with the assistance of other agencies if necessary. Meanwhile, the latest round of peace talks in the region has failed once again. Thanking His Excellency President Vladimir Putin for taking my call today, so I could gain an understanding of the situation that was unfolding between Russia and Ukraine. pic.twitter.com/jzuWXyIjfL I outlined our position on the conflict that has unfolded as well as our belief that the conflict should be resolved through mediation and negotiation between the parties and - if need be - with the help of agencies that can help bring a solution to the conflict. President Putin appreciated our balanced approach. We believe this position enables both parties to subject the conflict to mediation & negotiation. Based on our relations with the Russian Federation & as member of BRICS, South Africa has been approached to play a mediation role.